Volcanic Belt]]\n| volcanic_arc      = [[Central Volcanic Zone]]\n| volcanic_field    = \n| last_eruption     = 1,100 \u00b1 100 or 700 \u00b1 200 years ago\n| first_ascent      = [[Coropuna#First ascent|First ascents]]\n| easiest_route     = \n| normal_route      = \n| access            = \n}}\n'''Coropuna''' is a [[Volcano#Dormant|dormant]] [[Complex volcano|compound volcano]] located in the [[Andes]] mountains of southeast-central [[Peru]]. The upper reaches of Coropuna consist of several [[wikt:perennially|perennially]] snowbound conical summits, lending it the name '''Nevado Coropuna''' in Spanish. The complex extends over an area of {{convert|240|km2|abbr=off}} and its highest summit reaches an altitude of {{convert|6377|m|abbr=off}} above sea level. This makes the Coropuna complex the [[List of mountains in Peru|third-highest of Peru]]. Its thick ice cap is the most extensive in Earth's [[Tropics|tropical zone]], with several [[Glacier morphology#Outlet Glaciers|outlet glaciers]] stretching out to lower altitudes. Below an elevation of {{convert|5000|m|abbr=off}}, there are various vegetation belts which include trees, [[peat bog]]s, grasses and also [[agricultural]] areas and [[pastures]].\n\nThe Coropuna complex consists of several [[stratovolcano]]s. These are composed chiefly of [[ignimbrite]]s{{efn|[[Volcanic ash|Ash]] flows{{sfn|Herrmann|Bucksch|2014|p=1513}}}} and [[lava flow]]s on a [[basement (geology)|basement]] formed by [[Middle Miocene]] ignimbrites and lava flows. The Coropuna complex has been active for at least five million years, with the bulk of the current cone having been formed during the [[Quaternary]].{{efn|The age of man, including [[Pleistocene]] and [[Holocene]].{{sfn|Herrmann|Bucksch|2014|p=2296}}}} Coropuna has had two or three [[Holocene]] eruptions {{nowrap|2,100 \u00b1 200}} and either {{nowrap|1,100 \u00b1 100}} or {{nowrap|700 \u00b1 200 years}} ago which generated lava flows, plus an additional eruption which may have taken place some 6,000&nbsp;years ago. Current activity occurs exclusively in the form of [[hot spring]]s.\n\nCoropuna is located {{convert|150|km|abbr=off}} northwest of the city of [[Arequipa]]. People have lived on the slopes of Coropuna for millennia. The mountain was regarded as sacred by the [[Inca Empire|Inca]] and several archaeological sites have been discovered there, including the Inca sites of [[Mawk'allaqta, Castilla|Maucallacta]] and [[Acchaymarca]]. The mountain was considered one of the most important Inca religious sites in their realm; human sacrifices were performed on its slopes, Coropuna forms part of many local legends and the mountain is worshiped to the present day.\n\nThe ice cap of Coropuna, which during the [[Last Glacial Maximum]] (LGM) had expanded to over {{convert|500|km2|abbr=off}}, has been in [[Retreat of glaciers since 1850|retreat since at least 1850]]. Estimates published in 2018 imply that the ice cap will persist until about 2120. The retreat of the Coropuna glaciers threatens the water supply of tens of thousands of people relying upon its [[Drainage basin|watershed]], and interaction between volcanic activity and glacial effects has generated [[mudflow]]s that could be hazardous to surrounding populations. Because of this, the Peruvian geological agency, [[INGEMMET]], monitors Coropuna and has published a hazard map for the volcano.\n\n== Name and etymology ==\nIn [[Quechuan languages|Quechua]], {{lang|qu|puna}} means \"plateau\", and {{lang|qu|coro}} is a common component of toponyms such as with [[Coro Coro, Bolivia]], though its etymology is unclear.<ref name=\"Holmer1960\" /> The name may mean {{lang|qu|Qoripuna}}, \"Puna of Gold\",<ref name=\"Trawick2003\" /> \"golden mountain\",<ref name=\"MINCETUR2019\" /> \"cold, snowy\" or \"cut off at the top\".<ref name=\"Wilson2009\" /> The name is also spelled {{lang|qu|Qhuru Puna}}.<ref name=\"Besom2010\" /> The mountain is also called Nevado Coropuna; \"Nevado\" is the Spanish word for \"snowy\".{{sfn|Bromley|Hall|Rademaker|Todd|2011|p=305}} There is another volcano in the [[Andagua volcanic field|Andahua volcanic field]] which has the same name, but is completely separate.{{sfn|Cuber|Panajew|Ga\u0142a\u015b|2015|p=66}}\n\n== Geography and geomorphology ==\nCoropuna lies in the [[Andes]] of Peru,{{sfn|Bromley|Hall|Rademaker|Todd|2011|p=306}} on the border between the [[Castilla Province|Castilla]] and [[Condesuyos Province]]s{{sfn|Marinque|Marino|Enderlin|Edwards|2018|p=176}} of the [[Arequipa Department]].{{sfn|Forget|Thouret|Kuentz|Fontugne|2008|p=16}}{{sfn|Marinque|Marino|Enderlin|Edwards|2018|p=176}} Towns around the volcano belong to the [[Chuquibamba District|Chuquibamba]], [[Machaguay District|Machaguay]], [[Pampacolca District|Pampacolca]] and [[Viraco District]]s.{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=3}} The volcano can be reached on paved roads through the town of Andahua, either from [[Arequipa]] or through [[Aplao]] from the [[Pan-American Highway]].{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=4}} Roads also pass along the northern and western sides of the volcano.{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=10}}\n\n=== Regional ===\nCoropuna is a part of the Andes, which stretch northwards along the western coast of South America from [[Tierra del Fuego]] to [[Venezuela]] forming the longest mountain chain in the world.{{sfn|Cuber|Panajew|Ga\u0142a\u015b|2015|p=61}} More regionally, the volcano is in the {{interlanguage link|Cordillera Ampato|es}}, a mountain range which lies at an average of {{convert|100|km}} from the Pacific coastline,{{sfn|Schotterer|Delachaux|Ledru|Angelis|2009|p=28}} and contains nearly one hundred glaciers.{{sfn|Racoviteanu|Manley|Arnaud|Williams|2007|p=111}}\n\nCoropuna is in the [[Central Volcanic Zone]] of the Andes,{{sfn|Bromley|Hall|Rademaker|Todd|2011|p=306}}{{sfn|de Silva|Francis|1990|p=287}} which contains 44&nbsp;stratovolcanoes{{sfn|Cuber|Panajew|Ga\u0142a\u015b|2015|p=63}}{{Spaced en dash}}including many of the world's highest{{sfn|de Silva|Francis|1990|p=287}}{{Spaced en dash}}and several glaciated volcanoes.{{sfn|Bromley|Thouret|Schimmelpfennig|Mari\u00f1o|2019|p=3}} Besides Coropuna, some of the latter are [[Sara Sara]], [[Solimana (volcano)|Solimana]], [[Mismi]], [[Ampato]], [[Hualca Hualca]], [[Sabancaya]], [[Chachani]], [[Misti]], [[Ubinas]], [[Huaynaputina]], [[Tutupaca]], [[Yucamane]] and [[Casiri (Tacna)|Casiri]].{{sfn|Cuber|Panajew|Ga\u0142a\u015b|2015|p=62}}{{sfn|Weibel|Frangipane-Gysel|Hunziker|1978|p=247}} Also found nearby are [[Neogene]]-age [[caldera]]s.{{sfn|Cuber|Panajew|Ga\u0142a\u015b|2015|p=62}} Sixteen volcanoes in Peru are active or potentially active.{{sfn|Vela|C\u00e1ceres|Calder\u00f3n|Chijcheapaza|2016|p=4}}\n\nThere is no habitation on Coropuna above {{convert|5200|m}},{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=7}} but numerous villages dot the lower slopes.{{efn|Villages on the lower slopes of Corpuna include: [[Ocororuro]], [[Arma (Peru)|Arma]], [[Maucallacta (town)|Maucallacta]], [[Purhua Purhua]], [[Chaupipuna (town)|Chaupipuna]], [[Utchu-Amayani]], [[Torilla (Peruvian town)|Torilla]], [[Patilla (town)|Patilla]], [[Pallca (town)|Pallca]], [[Alco Llacta]], [[Viques (town)|Viques]], [[Campanayo]], [[Pecoy]], [[Tagre]], [[Pillcull]], [[Chupacca]], [[Chipcama]], [[Cabra Grande]], [[Pampacolca (town)|Pampacolca]], [[Huncor]], [[Huanjo]], [[Santa Maria (town in Peru)|Santa Maria]], [[Toma de Hayllaura]] and [[Huayllaura]].{{sfn|Forget|Thouret|Kuentz|Fontugne|2008|p=18}}}} [[Agriculture]] and [[animal husbandry]] are the most common economic activities;{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=61}} there are [[copper]] and [[gold]] [[mining|mine]]s as well.{{sfn|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|Steinm\u00fcller|1998|p=52}} The city of Arequipa lies {{convert|150|km|abbr=on}} to the southeast.{{sfn|Bromley|Hall|Rademaker|Todd|2011|p=306}}\n\n=== Local ===\n\n==== General outline ====\n[[File:CoropunaSouthViewUSGS.jpg|thumb|right|alt=An elongated snow-covered ridge rises from a dark landscape with valleys|Coropuna seen from the south in 1988]]\nSeen from above, Coropuna has a pear-shaped outline{{sfn|Weibel|Frangipane-Gysel|Hunziker|1978|p=246}} and is a {{convert|20|km|abbr=on}} east{{en dash}}west ridge{{sfn|Forget|Thouret|Kuentz|Fontugne|2008|p=16}} that features four summits that are separated by broad [[Saddle (landform)|saddles]].{{sfn|Bromley|Hall|Rademaker|Todd|2011|p=306}}{{sfn|Bromley|Hall|Schaefer|Winckler|2011|p=38}} In addition, there is another summit north of the east{{en dash}}west trend.<ref name=\"GVP\" /> A {{convert|5558|m|abbr=on}} high subsidiary peak named Cerro Cuncaicha lies east of Coropuna,{{sfn|Palenque|Ni\u00f1o de Guzm\u00e1n|Choque|\u00c1lvarez|2018|p=105}} it is a stratovolcano.<ref name=\"Mapa2017\" /> Coropuna covers a surface area of {{convert|240|km2}}{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=35}} and its various main summits rise about {{convert|3|km|spell=in}} above the surrounding plateau.{{sfn|Bromley|Thouret|Schimmelpfennig|Mari\u00f1o|2019|p=3}}\n\nThe volcano is formed from alternating layers of ignimbrite and lava,{{sfn|Weibel|Frangipane-Gysel|Hunziker|1978|p=246}} and consists of coalesced stratovolcanoes{{sfn|\u00dabeda Palenque|2013|p=124}} and seven separate [[Lava dome#Lava coul\u00e9es|coulee]]s.{{sfn|Forget|Thouret|Kuentz|Fontugne|2008|p=17}} Ice cover makes discerning its structure difficult,{{sfn|de Silva|Francis|1990|p=292}} but about{{sfn|de Silva|Francis|1990|p=292}} six separate peaks{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=35}}{{sfn|Bullard|1962|p=444}}<ref name=\"IGdP2018\" /> as well as six not readily recognisable [[summit crater]]s  have been counted.{{sfn|Forget|Thouret|Kuentz|Fontugne|2008|p=18}}{{sfn|Weibel|Frangipane-Gysel|Hunziker|1978|p=246}} Additional [[lava dome]]s form a southeastward trending line on the southwestern side of the volcano{{sfn|Forget|Thouret|Kuentz|Fontugne|2008|p=18}} and [[dike (geology)|dike]]s crop out close to Lake [[Pallarcocha]].{{sfn|Forget|Thouret|Kuentz|Fontugne|2008|p=18}} Coropuna overlies the margin of a buried caldera.<ref name=\"Yates2013\" />\n\nThe higher elevations of Coropuna consist of an ice cap and glaciated terrain{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=35}} but old\u00a0[[lava flow]]s with gentle slopes{{sfn|Racoviteanu|Manley|Arnaud|Williams|2007|p=112}} and [[Lava|blocky lava]] crop out from underneath the ice.{{sfn|Cuber|Panajew|Ga\u0142a\u015b|2015|p=63}} Regions of [[hydrothermal]]ly altered rocks, lava flows, [[pyroclastic flow]]s and areas covered by [[volcanic ash]] occur all around the mountain.{{sfn|Forget|Thouret|Kuentz|Fontugne|2008|p=18}} Glacial activity has eroded these volcanic rocks, carving valleys into them or removing them altogether.{{sfn|Palenque|Ni\u00f1o de Guzm\u00e1n|Choque|\u00c1lvarez|2018|p=104}} This process created [[U-shaped valley]]s such as Buenavista, Cospanja and Tuilaqui on the southern flank, and glacial valleys such as Chaque, Mapa Mayo, R\u00edo Blanco, Torcom and Ullulo on the northern slopes.{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=12}} Glacial valleys of Coropuna are up to {{convert|300|m|abbr=on}} deep and {{convert|7|km|abbr=on|spell=in}} long.{{sfn|Forget|Thouret|Kuentz|Fontugne|2008|p=19}}\n\nThere are several collapse [[Cliff|scarps]] on the mountain, especially around its central sector.<ref name=\"Mapa2017\" /> A [[sector collapse]] took place on the southwestern flank and formed a [[landslide]] deposit as well as a horseshoe-shaped valley that was later filled by glaciers.{{sfn|Forget|Thouret|Kuentz|Fontugne|2008|p=19}} Also on the southern side, mud-water flow deposits have been found in the Capiza River valley and appear to relate to Coropuna;{{sfn|Garc\u00eda Z\u00fa\u00f1iga|Mari\u00f1o Salazar|Valdivia Humerez|2018|p=117}} at least eight such debris flows have been identified.{{sfn|Garc\u00eda Z\u00fa\u00f1iga|Mari\u00f1o Salazar|Valdivia Humerez|2018|p=120}} [[Lahar]]s (mudflows) have reached the [[Colca River]] valley.{{sfn|Garc\u00eda Z\u00fa\u00f1iga|Mari\u00f1o Salazar|Valdivia Humerez|2018|p=118}} Lahars are dangerous phenomena owing to their high speed and density, causing large scale destruction and fatalities.{{sfn|Garc\u00eda Z\u00fa\u00f1iga|Mari\u00f1o Salazar|Valdivia Humerez|2018|p=117}}\n\n==== Lakes and rivers ====\n[[File:COROPUNA LAKE - panoramio.jpg|thumb|right|alt=A barren, rock-strewn terrain with two ice-covered mountains in the background; to the left lies a blue lake and to the right a scarp|Coropuna seen from Lake Pallacocha]]\nLakes  lie on the flanks of the volcano.{{sfn|Bromley|Thouret|Schimmelpfennig|Mari\u00f1o|2019|p=5}} These include [[Lake Pallarcocha]] on the southwestern flank on formerly glaciated terrain,{{sfn|\u00dabeda|Palacios|V\u00e1zquez-Selem|2012|pp=3\u20134}} Laguna Pucaylla on Coropuna's northeastern side and Laguna Caracara on the southeastern side. A number of streams and rivers originate on the mountain. Clockwise around Coropuna, these include Quebrada Chauqui-Huayco, Rio Amayani on the northern side, Quebrada Chinchina/Infernillo, Quebrada Jollpa, Quebrada Caspanja with the lake Laguna Caracara, Quebrada Buena Vista, Quebrada Tuallqui, Rio Testane on the southern flank, Rio de Huayllaura on the southwestern flank, Quebrada del Apacheta,{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=10}} Quebrada Sigue Chico{{sfn|Bromley|Schaefer|Winckler|Hall|2009|p=2515}} and Quebrada Sepulturayoc on the western flank.{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=10}} The Rio Blanco and Rio Amayani eventually form the [[Rio Arma]],{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=21}} while the Rio Capiza discharges water from Coropuna to the Colca River.{{sfn|Caldas Vidal|1993|p=10}} During the dry season, most of these rivers do not carry substantial discharge.{{sfn|Weibel|Frangipane-Gysel|Hunziker|1978|p=245}}\n\nThe volcano is situated on a [[drainage divide]].{{sfn|Silverio|Jaquet|2012|p=5878}} To the west the Rio Arma is a tributary of the [[Oco\u00f1a River]], while to the east the Colca River is part of the [[Majes River]] watershed.{{sfn|Palenque|Ni\u00f1o de Guzm\u00e1n|Choque|\u00c1lvarez|2018|p=104}} An [[endorheic]] area that receives meltwater from the volcano also exists northeast from Coropuna, on Pampa Pucaylla{{sfn|Palenque|Ni\u00f1o de Guzm\u00e1n|Choque|\u00c1lvarez|2018|p=108}} where the lake of the same name lies.{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=10}}\n\n==== Surrounding terrain ====\nCoropuna rises {{convert|2|km|abbr=on}} above the surrounding terrain{{sfn|Campos|2015|p=2}}{{sfn|Bromley|Hall|Schaefer|Winckler|2011|p=38}} from a base elevation of {{convert|4500|m|abbr=on}},{{sfn|Forget|Thouret|Kuentz|Fontugne|2008|p=16}} and about {{convert|3.5|km}} on the southern side where the Rio Llacllaja has incised the underlying [[basement (geology)|basement]]{{sfn|Campos|2015|p=2}}{{sfn|Bromley|Hall|Schaefer|Winckler|2011|p=38}} almost to the foot of the volcano, forming sharp, amphitheatre-like valleys.{{sfn|Weibel|Frangipane-Gysel|Hunziker|1978|p=245}} In general, many deep valleys cut into the flanks of the volcano{{sfn|Vela|C\u00e1ceres|Calder\u00f3n|Chijcheapaza|2016|p=9}} and give the mountain an \"impressive topographic relief\".<ref name=\"GVP\"/>\n\nThe region is characterised by high plateaus separated by deep [[canyon]]s, including some of the world's deepest gorges{{sfn|Bromley|Schaefer|Winckler|Hall|2009|p=2515}} that reach depths of {{convert|600|-|3000|m|abbr=on}}.{{sfn|Thouret|Gunnell|Jicha|Paquette|2017|p=2}} Apart from river erosion, giant landslides have affected the [[Altiplano]] below Coropuna,{{sfn|G\u00f3mez|Mac\u00edas|Arce|S\u00e1nchez-Nu\u00f1ez|2012|p=1025}} such as the Chuquibamba landslide, which took place over the last 120,000{{nbsp;}}years in the form of multiple collapse events within a [[fault (geology)|fault]]-controlled basin.{{sfn|Thouret|Gunnell|Jicha|Paquette|2017|p=14}}\n\nGeomorphologically, Coropuna lies at the edge of the Altiplano high plateau on the [[Cordillera Occidental (Peru)|Western Cordillera]] mountain range;{{sfn|Kuentz|Mera|Ledru|Thouret|2007|p=1764}} in the Central Andes this mountain chain is split into two ranges{{Spaced en dash}}the western and the eastern Cordillera{{Spaced en dash}}separated by the Altiplano.{{sfn|Bullard|1962|p=443}} The Pucuncho Basin{{sfn|Bromley|Hall|Rademaker|Todd|2011|p=305}} and [[Firura]] volcano lie north of Coropuna, while Solimana volcano is northwest from Coropuna.{{sfn|Bromley|Hall|Rademaker|Todd|2011|p=306}} Sara Sara is another volcano in the area.{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=35}} A large [[lava dome]] lies northwest of Coropuna{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=10}} while [[Puma Ranra (Castilla-Condesuyos)|Cerro Pumaranra]], a {{convert|5089|m|abbr=on}}{{sfn|Palenque|Ni\u00f1o de Guzm\u00e1n|Choque|\u00c1lvarez|2018|p=105}} eroded volcano, is to the northeast.{{sfn|Forget|Thouret|Kuentz|Fontugne|2008|p=18}} {{convert|19|km|abbr=on}} west-southwest from Coropuna lies the {{convert|4855|m|abbr=on}} high [[Antapuna]],{{sfn|Dornbusch|2002|p=116}} while the [[Andahua]] \"[[Valley of the Volcanoes]]\" is {{convert|20|km|abbr=on}} east-northeast of Coropuna.{{sfn|de Silva|Francis|1990|p=298}}\n\n=== Elevation and size ===\n[[File:Coropuna Este (30293366316).jpg|thumb|right|alt=A gentle, ice-covered ridge with hump-like summits|Coropuna Este]]\nCoropuna is the largest{{sfn|Venturelli|Fragipane|Weibel|Antiga|1978|p=214}} and highest volcano in Peru, highest peak of the {{ill|Cordillera Ampato|es}}{{sfn|Campos|2015|p=2}} and the third-highest mountain in the Peru.<ref name=\"Trawick2003\" /><ref name=\"MINCETUR2019\" /> The highest point of Coropuna is the northwestern dome<ref name=\"GVP\" />{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=35}} named Coropuna Casulla,{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=3}} with {{convert|6377|m}} elevation.<ref name=\"GVP\" /><ref name=\"MdA2019\" /><ref name=\"IGdP2018\" /> [[Mountaineering]] sources also cite an elevation of {{convert|6425|m}} for the El Toro summit,<ref name=\"Biggar2015\" /><ref name=\"AAC1990\" /> which would make Coropuna the 22nd highest mountain in the Andes.{{sfn|Cuber|Panajew|Ga\u0142a\u015b|2015|p=63}}{{efn|Other estimates of its height are {{convert|6380|m|abbr=on}};{{sfn|Kuentz|Ledru|Thouret|2011|p=1216}}{{sfn|Thouret|Juvigne|Mari\u00f1o|Moscol|2002|p=3}} {{convert|6426|m|abbr=on}}{{sfn|Bromley|Hall|Schaefer|Winckler|2011|p=38}}{{sfn|Weibel|Frangipane-Gysel|Hunziker|1978|p=245}}{{sfn|Campos|2015|p=2}} on the western summit;{{sfn|Weibel|Frangipane-Gysel|Hunziker|1978|p=245}} {{convert|6446|m|abbr=on}};{{sfn|Silverio|Herold|Peduzzi|2010|p=314}} and {{convert|6450|m}}.{{sfn|Bromley|Hall|Rademaker|Todd|2011|p=305}}}}\n\nEstimates on the height of Coropuna have changed over time. In the 19th century, it was one of the candidates for \"highest mountain in Peru\", with the Mapa del Per\u00fa (Map of Peru) of [[Antonio Raimondi]] giving an estimated height of {{convert|6949|m|abbr=on}}; other candidates were peaks in the [[Cordillera Blanca]].{{sfn|Wise|2004|p=97}} In 1910 it was believed that the volcano was over {{convert|23000|ft|m|order=flip|abbr=on}} high and thus the highest mountain in South America ahead of [[Aconcagua]],<ref name=\"Bingham2010\" /><ref name=\"Bandelier1910\" /> although a North American expedition during the preceding year had determined that Coropuna was not the highest as they only found an elevation of {{convert|6615|m|abbr=on}} and [[Huascaran]] is higher than this.{{sfn|Wise|2004|p=98}} Varying snow elevations might also lead to varying height estimates.<ref name=\"Biggar2015\" />\n\nCoropuna has several summits (up to ten overall according to one count){{sfn|Weibel|Frangipane-Gysel|Hunziker|1978|p=246}} which exceed {{convert|6000|m|abbr=on}} elevation,{{sfn|Silverio|Jaquet|2012|p=5878}} plus a {{convert|5623|m|abbr=on}} northern summit.{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=3}} Those with individual names are the northwestern Coropuna Casulla at {{convert|6377|m}},{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=35}} El Toro,<ref name=\"Biggar2015\" /><ref name=\"AAC1990\" /> the western Nevado Pallacocha at {{convert|6171|m|abbr=on}}, the central Coropuna Central II at {{convert|6161|m|abbr=on}},<ref name=\"Hernandez2013\" /> Escalera in the western sector of the volcano, Paiche in the central sector,<ref name=\"Mapa2017\" /> and Coropuna Este{{sfn|Bromley|Hall|Rademaker|Todd|2011|p=308}} and Yana Ranra in the eastern sector.<ref name=\"Mapa2017\" />\n\n== Ice cap ==\n[[File:Nevado Coropuna, Peru.JPG|thumb|right|Coropuna\u2019s ice cap seen from space in 2010|alt=A roughly pear-shaped ice area, from which valleys emanate, lies within a multicolored landscape, as seen from a satellite image]]\nCoropuna features the largest [[ice cap]] of the tropics.{{sfn|Garc\u00eda Z\u00fa\u00f1iga|Mari\u00f1o Salazar|Valdivia Humerez|2018|p=117}} As of 2014 it was {{convert|8.5|km|abbr=on}} wide and {{convert|11|km|abbr=on}} long.{{sfn|Marinque|Marino|Enderlin|Edwards|2018|p=179}} It is larger than the [[Quelccaya Ice Cap]] {{convert|250|km|abbr=on}} farther northeast, which was considered to be the largest,{{sfn|Marinque|Marino|Enderlin|Edwards|2018|p=179}}{{sfn|Palenque|Ni\u00f1o de Guzm\u00e1n|Choque|\u00c1lvarez|2018|p=101}} but has since shrunk to a size less than Coropuna's.<ref name=\"NOAA2018\" /> A subsidiary peak named Cerro Cuncaicha, east of Coropuna, has a small ice cap as well.{{sfn|Bromley|Hall|Rademaker|Todd|2011|p=307}} In general, Peruvian glaciers form the bulk of the world's tropical glaciers.{{sfn|Silverio|Jaquet|2012|p=5876}} The ice cap consists of three ice domes and many glaciers.{{sfn|Marinque|Marino|Enderlin|Edwards|2018|p=179}} Perennial [[snow field]]s are present on Coropuna, sometimes making it hard to measure the true extent of glaciation or glacier retreat.{{sfn|Bromley|Hall|Schaefer|Winckler|2011|p=38}}\n\nOn average, the ice cap of Coropuna is about {{convert|80.8|m|abbr=on}} thick,{{sfn|Silverio|Herold|Peduzzi|2010|p=320}} with maximum thicknesses exceeding {{convert|180|m|abbr=on}}.{{sfn|Silverio|Herold|Peduzzi|2010|p=321}} In 2003{{en dash}}2004 the ice cap had a volume of about {{convert|3.69|km3}} [[snow water equivalent]]s.{{sfn|Silverio|2018|p=49}} [[Ice core]]s have been taken from the Coropuna ice cap{{sfn|Weide|Fritz|Brinson|Thompson|2017|p=3}} and from a summit crater;<ref name=\"Lin2018\" /> one of these ice cores covers a timespan beginning from 20,000{{nbsp;}}years ago.{{sfn|Engel|Skrzypek|Chuman|\u0160efrna|2014|p=63}}\n\n[[Penitente (snow formation)|Penitente]]s{{sfn|Schotterer|Delachaux|Ledru|Angelis|2009|p=28}} reaching heights of {{convert|2|m|abbr=on}}{{sfn|Cuber|Panajew|Ga\u0142a\u015b|2015|p=67}} and [[serac]]s (blocks of ice in glaciers delimited by cracks) occur on the glaciers,{{sfn|Forget|Thouret|Kuentz|Fontugne|2008|p=18}} while debris cover is rare.{{sfn|Marinque|Marino|Enderlin|Edwards|2018|p=178}} Mudflows (lahars) originated from the ice cap{{sfn|Campos|2015|p=2}} and left deposits at the bottom of valleys.{{sfn|Vela|C\u00e1ceres|Calder\u00f3n|Chijcheapaza|2016|p=9}}\n\n=== Glaciers and periglacial phenomena ===\nA number of glaciers flow down from the ice cap,{{sfn|Forget|Thouret|Kuentz|Fontugne|2008|p=18}} their number variously estimated to be  23,{{sfn|Marinque|Marino|Enderlin|Edwards|2018|p=179}} 17{{sfn|Silverio|2018|p=45}}{{sfn|Silverio|Jaquet|2012|p=5878}} and 15.{{sfn|Bromley|Hall|Schaefer|Winckler|2011|p=38}} Some glaciers have been named; on the southwestern flank two glaciers are known as {{lang|es|Azufrioc}}&nbsp;1 and 2, three {{lang|es|Rio Blanco}}&nbsp;1 through 3 and six {{lang|es|Tuialqui}} 1 through 6.{{sfn|Campos|2015|p=7}} Eighteen separate accumulation areas have been found as well.{{sfn|Forget|Thouret|Kuentz|Fontugne|2008|p=24}} There are no substantive valley glaciers presently on Coropuna{{sfn|de Silva|Francis|1990|p=292}} and some glaciers, especially in the eastern side, emanate from [[cirque]]s.{{sfn|Forget|Thouret|Kuentz|Fontugne|2008|p=18}} The ongoing downward movement of the ice on Coropuna produces [[icequake]]s.<ref name=\"IGdP2018\" />\n\nGlaciers descend to elevations of about {{convert|5100|to|5300|m|abbr=on}} on the southern flank, and to about {{convert|5500|to|5800|m|abbr=on}} on the northern flank.{{sfn|Bromley|Hall|Rademaker|Todd|2011|p=306}}{{sfn|Marinque|Marino|Enderlin|Edwards|2018|p=179}}{{sfn|Forget|Thouret|Kuentz|Fontugne|2008|p=17}} This is higher than the [[freezing level]], owing to the dry climate;{{sfn|Campos|2015|p=2}} the freezing level at Coropuna lies at about {{convert|4900|m|abbr=on}} elevation.{{sfn|Bromley|Hall|Schaefer|Winckler|2011|p=38}} In 2001, the ice limits were located at elevations of {{convert|5300|m|abbr=on}} on the southern and at {{convert|5600|m|abbr=on}} on the northern flank.{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=9}}\n\n[[Moraine]]s are mostly found on Coropuna's northern and southern side{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=10}} and reach lengths of {{convert|3|to|8|km|abbr=on}}, with longer moraines on the northern flank.{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=12}} In general, moraines on Coropuna are steep and have prominent crests as they are little eroded.{{sfn|Bromley|Hall|Rademaker|Todd|2011|p=307}} Grey-coloured, fresh moraines up to {{convert|500|m|abbr=on}} from the ice cap may reflect the position of the glaciers before the onset of [[glacier retreat]] which has left small mounds that often contain ice between these moraines and the ice cap{{sfn|Bromley|Hall|Rademaker|Todd|2011|p=307}} and small, discontinuous moraines.{{sfn|Bromley|Hall|Rademaker|Todd|2011|p=310}}\n\nApart from normal glaciers, 78&nbsp;[[rock glacier]]s have been counted on Coropuna, but only 11 of them are considered to be active.{{sfn|Forget|Thouret|Kuentz|Fontugne|2008|p=28}} [[Permafrost]] has also been reported on Coropuna.<ref name=\"UbedaYoshikawa2015\" /> [[Cryoturbation]],{{sfn|Gal\u00e1n|Linares Perea|2012|p=15}} [[gelifluction]], [[patterned ground]]s,{{sfn|Weibel|Frangipane-Gysel|Hunziker|1978|p=246}} [[solifluction]]{{sfn|Gal\u00e1n|Linares Perea|2012|p=48}} and other [[periglacial]] landforms are noticeable{{sfn|Weibel|Frangipane-Gysel|Hunziker|1978|p=246}} at over {{convert|4500|m|abbr=on}} elevation.{{sfn|Weibel|Frangipane-Gysel|Hunziker|1978|p=246}}\n\n==== Recent area and retreat ====\n[[File:Coropuna ice cap extent 1950-2015.svg|alt=While individual trend series of the extent of Coropuna's ice cap often heavily diverge from each other, a strong declining tendency is noticeable|thumb|upright=1.35|Extent of the ice cap over the years, from various sources:{{efn|As cited in Forget et al (2008),{{sfn|Forget|Thouret|Kuentz|Fontugne|2008|p=17}} Palenque et al (2018),{{sfn|Palenque|Ni\u00f1o de Guzm\u00e1n|Choque|\u00c1lvarez|2018|p=101}} Marinque et al (2018),{{sfn|Marinque|Marino|Enderlin|Edwards|2018|p=178}} Silverio (2018),{{sfn|Silverio|2018|p=45}} Silverio, Herold & Peduzzi (2010),{{sfn|Silverio|Herold|Peduzzi|2010|p=318}} and Silverio & Jaquet (2012).{{sfn|Silverio|Jaquet|2012|p=5882}}}}]]\n\nMeasuring the surface area of Coropuna's ice cap is difficult as seasonal snow can be mistaken for ice,{{sfn|Marinque|Marino|Enderlin|Edwards|2018|p=180}} and different studies come to various conclusions about the retreat rate, due to the use of different time periods and methodological practices. However, all studies conclude that the net retreat trend is obvious and that the ice cap is diminishing.<ref name=\"Veettil2017\" /> Retreat rates shortly before 2009 reached 13{{nbsp;}}percent in only 21{{nbsp;}}years.{{sfn|Campos|2015|p=12}} Between 1980 and 2014 the ice cap shrank at a rate of {{convert|0.409|km2/year|mi2/year||abbr=}}{{sfn|Marinque|Marino|Enderlin|Edwards|2018|p=179}} with a 2015 estimate amounting to {{convert|0.5|km2/year|mi2/year}},<ref name=\"Kochtitzky2015\" /> and a brief slowdown observed during the late 1990s and early 2000s.{{sfn|Marinque|Marino|Enderlin|Edwards|2018|p=181}} Total shrinkage has been estimated to amount to 26{{nbsp;}}percent between 1962 and 2000, and by 18{{nbsp;}}percent between 1955 and 2007.{{sfn|Campos|2015|p=2}}\n\nThe Coropuna ice cap retreat follows the pattern recorded elsewhere in Peru such as in the Cordillera Blanca, [[Cordillera Vilcanota]] and the mountains Ampato, Quelccaya and Sabancaya.{{sfn|Forget|Thouret|Kuentz|Fontugne|2008|p=31}} All of this retreat is attributed to [[global warming]],{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=9}} and tends to increase during [[El Ni\u00f1o]] years owing to a drier climate. The glaciers lose mass through both [[sublimation (phase transition)|sublimation]] and [[melting]]. This meltwater rarely forms streams, though some do exist. The Quebrada Ullulo on the northern side is the largest such meltwater stream.{{sfn|Bromley|Hall|Schaefer|Winckler|2011|p=38}}\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" widths=\"360\">\nFile:Coropuna glacier areas.png|alt=The ice area has been steadily decreasing since 1950 and it may completely disappear in the future|Glacier trends and extrapolation\nFile:Coropuna ice profile.png|alt=Radar display of a transect through the ice cap|Ice profile\nFile:Ice loss Coropuna-2.png|alt=The thickest ice lies in the western portion, while marginal ice is thinner|Ice thickness\nFile:Radar profile and glacier evolution Coropuna.png|alt=A number of transects across the ice cap have been made, with the ice cap retreating at its margins|Ice schematics\n</gallery>\n\n=== Glacial history ===\nBefore the first human settlement of the area,{{sfn|Sandweiss|\u00c1lvarez|Reid|Leach|2014|p=468}}{{sfn|Sandweiss|\u00c1lvarez|Reid|Leach|2014|pp=466\u2013467}} the ice cap on Coropuna was much larger than today, with its surface exceeding {{convert|500|km2}}{{sfn|Palenque|Ni\u00f1o de Guzm\u00e1n|Choque|\u00c1lvarez|2018|p=102}} and its glaciers descending to much lower elevations.{{sfn|Bromley|Schaefer|Winckler|Hall|2009|p=2515}} Additionally, glaciers also expanded from the mountains Pumaranra, Pucaylla and Cuncaicha to the east of Coropuna.{{sfn|Palenque|Ni\u00f1o de Guzm\u00e1n|Choque|\u00c1lvarez|2018|p=107}} They covered the Pampa Pucaylla northeast from Coropuna and descended the Jellojello valley and other valleys to the east.{{sfn|\u00dabeda|Palacios|V\u00e1zquez-Selem|2012|p=3}} [[Glacial valley]]s radiate from Coropuna,{{sfn|de Silva|Francis|1990|p=292}} and [[glaciofluvial]] landforms are associated with moraines.{{sfn|Bromley|Hall|Schaefer|Winckler|2011|p=38}}\n\nRegional climate oscillations are recorded in the ice masses of Coropuna.{{sfn|\u00dabeda Palenque|2013|p=24}} The glacial history of the volcano has been reconstructed with [[tephrochronology]] (using dated [[tephra]] layers such as those from the 1600 Huaynaputina eruptions), [[radiocarbon dating]]{{sfn|Forget|Thouret|Kuentz|Fontugne|2008|p=17}} and [[surface exposure dating]] using [[helium-3]].{{sfn|Bromley|Hall|Schaefer|Winckler|2011|p=38}} Three separate moraine generations<ref name=\"Mapa2017\" /> and about five separate glacial stages have been recorded on the volcano.<ref name=\"GSA2007\" /> Glacial advances on Coropuna appear to be synchronous to advances of the ice sheets in the [[Northern Hemisphere]].{{sfn|Forget|Thouret|Kuentz|Fontugne|2008|p=30}} Glaciers developed on other mountains in the region as well.{{sfn|Dornbusch|2002|p=123}}\n\n==== Last glacial maximum ====\nDuring the [[Last Glacial Maximum]] (LGM) 25,000{{en dash}}20,000{{nbsp;}}years ago,{{sfn|Bromley|Hall|Rademaker|Todd|2011|p=308}} valley glaciers on Coropuna were considerably longer than today.{{sfn|Forget|Thouret|Kuentz|Fontugne|2008|p=17}} The longest glacier, at {{convert|12|km|abbr=on}}, was in the Quebrada Ullulo.{{sfn|Bromley|Hall|Rademaker|Todd|2011|p=308}} The glaciers had a cover of boulders and [[gravel]] and formed tall moraines, and both lateral and terminal moraines where [[outlet glacier]]s ended. At the crest, these moraines were as much as {{convert|100|m|abbr=on}} high, {{convert|8|km|abbr=on}} long, and {{convert|5|-|10|m|abbr=on}} wide.{{sfn|Bromley|Hall|Rademaker|Todd|2011|pp=307\u2013308}} On the northern flank, moraine systems have been observed in the Santiago, Ullulo,{{sfn|Bromley|Hall|Schaefer|Winckler|2011|p=39}} Kea\u00f1a, Que\u00f1ua Ranra, Cuncaicha, Pommulca and Huajra Huire valleys,{{sfn|Palenque|Ni\u00f1o de Guzm\u00e1n|Choque|\u00c1lvarez|2018|p=108}} while the southeastern flank was covered by glaciers in the Yanaorco, Viques, Cospanja, Buena Vista Este, Buena Vista Oeste and Huasi valleys.{{sfn|\u00dabeda|Palacios|V\u00e1zquez-Selem|2012|p=3}} [[Riegel (glacial)|Rock bar]]s occur in some glacial valleys on the southern and southwestern side of the volcano.{{sfn|Forget|Thouret|Kuentz|Fontugne|2008|p=18}} There are large cirques around Cerro Cuncaicha.{{sfn|Bromley|Hall|Rademaker|Todd|2011|p=307}}{{sfn|Forget|Thouret|Kuentz|Fontugne|2008|p=17}}\n\nThe LGM ice cap had an area of at least {{convert|365|km2|abbr=on}}, with glaciers descending to {{convert|3780|-|4540|m|abbr=on}} elevation. Glacier ends were lower on the northern{{sfn|Bromley|Hall|Rademaker|Todd|2011|p=308}} and western sides, probably due to airflow-mediated variations in sublimation.{{sfn|Bromley|Hall|Rademaker|Todd|2011|p=312}} The growth of the ice cap has been explained by a decrease of the [[equilibrium line altitude]] of about {{convert|750|m|abbr=on|adj=on}}. Assuming constant precipitation, temperatures may have decreased by {{convert|4.5|-|5.5|C-change}}.{{sfn|Heine|2019|p=264}} The glaciers began to retreat between 12,000 and 11,000{{nbsp;}}years ago.{{sfn|Palenque|Ni\u00f1o de Guzm\u00e1n|Choque|\u00c1lvarez|2018|p=118}}\n\n==== Other glacial periods ====\nIce has been present on Coropuna for at least 80,000{{nbsp;}}years.<ref name=\"\u00dabedaPalacio2012\" /> At least two pre-LGM advances spread beyond the area that was covered with ice during the LGM,{{sfn|Bromley|Hall|Schaefer|Winckler|2011|p=38}} with an expansion occurring in particular in the eastern sector of the volcano.{{sfn|Heine|2019|p=269}} Moraines older than [[marine isotope stage]] 2 are widespread.{{sfn|Heine|2019|p=262}} Those close to the village of Viraco may date back 40,000{{en dash}}45,000{{nbsp;}}years and thus be part of an earlier glaciation,{{sfn|Forget|Thouret|Kuentz|Fontugne|2008|p=22}} and old dates of 47,000{{en dash}}31,000 and 61,000{{en dash}}37,000{{nbsp;}}years ago in the Huayllaura and Sigue Chico valleys could reflect even larger glacier expansions during marine isotope stage&nbsp;3 or 4.{{sfn|Palenque|Ni\u00f1o de Guzm\u00e1n|Choque|\u00c1lvarez|2018|p=113}}\n\nGlaciers retreated after the end of the last glacial maximum 20,000{{en dash}}18,000{{nbsp;}}years ago and then re-expanded.<ref name=\"GSA2007\" /> During the [[Late Glacial|Lateglacial]], a group of moraines formed between the position of the LGM moraines and the position of the recent moraines,{{sfn|Bromley|Hall|Rademaker|Todd|2011|p=307}} with one lateglacial advance dated to either 13,400{{en dash}}10,000 or 13,900{{en dash}}11,900{{nbsp;}}years ago.{{sfn|Heine|2019|p=263}} Full glacial conditions lasted until 10,000{{en dash}}9,000{{nbsp;}}years ago;<ref name=\"\u00dabedaPalacio2012\" /> minor advances took place about {{nowrap|13,000{{en dash}}9,000 years}} ago, and again some 6,000&nbsp;years ago.{{sfn|\u00dabeda|Palacios|V\u00e1zquez-Selem|2012|p=5}} The late glacial advances coincide with similar glacier expansions worldwide{{sfn|Bromley|Schaefer|Winckler|Hall|2009|p=2520}} and some of them may correlate with the [[Younger Dryas]] cold period or the [[Antarctic Cold Reversal]].{{sfn|Bromley|Hall|Schaefer|Winckler|2011|p=42}} During the [[Little Ice Age]], glaciers on Coropuna did not expand much, although some rock glaciers might have formed during that time. The glaciers descended to {{convert|4900|m|abbr=on}} elevation.{{sfn|Forget|Thouret|Kuentz|Fontugne|2008|p=30}}\n\n=== Importance as a source of water ===\nGlaciers in Peru are important sources of water for local communities and for [[hydropower]] generation, especially during the dry season; their shrinkage is thus of concern.{{sfn|Marinque|Marino|Enderlin|Edwards|2018|p=175}} A 2003 study by Bryan G. Mark and Geoffrey O. Seltzer estimated that about 30{{nbsp;}}percent of the dry season runoff in the Cordillera Blanca comes from glaciers.{{sfn|Marinque|Marino|Enderlin|Edwards|2018|p=183}} Meltwater from the glaciers on Coropuna sustains the [[baseflow]] of the rivers{{sfn|Silverio|2018|p=44}} during dry periods;{{sfn|Silverio|2018|p=45}} Coropuna is an important source of water for the valleys of the surrounding areas and for the desert-like [[piedmont]],{{sfn|Forget|Thouret|Kuentz|Fontugne|2008|p=31}} with an estimated 38,000&nbsp;people depending directly or indirectly on water originating from it.{{sfn|Silverio|Herold|Peduzzi|2010|p=314}} This water supply is threatened by the retreat of the glaciers{{sfn|Forget|Thouret|Kuentz|Fontugne|2008|p=31}} and would require costly mitigation measures to compensate for its reduction. The Peruvian government is making preparations for Coropuna ceasing to be a contributor to the local water supply by 2025; a 2018 study and re-evaluation of past data concluded that the ice cap should persist until about 2120, and recommends that greater ''[[in situ]]'' monitoring of Coropuna's glaciers is needed to aid future planning and mitigation.{{sfn|Marinque|Marino|Enderlin|Edwards|2018|p=182}}\n\n== Geology ==\n\n=== Regional setting ===\n[[File:South American plates.png|thumb|The larger [[List of tectonic plates|tectonic plates]] in South America|alt=South America has been a stable continent since the Paleozoic, but the whole Pacific coast is geologically very active]]\nOff the coast of Peru, the [[Nazca Plate]] [[Subduction|subducts]] beneath the [[South American Plate]] at a rate of {{convert|9|cm/year|in/year}}.{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=59}} This subduction process, along with the subduction of the [[Antarctic Plate]] also underneath the South American Plate, is responsible for the volcanism in the Andes and the uplift of the mountain chain.<ref name=\"Stern2004\" /> In the Cordillera Occidental (Western Cordillera) uplift commenced about 50{{nbsp;}}million years ago in the [[Eocene]], paused until 25&nbsp;million{{nbsp;}}years ago in the [[Oligocene]], and increased substantially after about 10{{nbsp;}}million years ago in the [[Miocene]].{{sfn|Thouret|Gunnell|Jicha|Paquette|2017|p=3}} Andean uplift in the area of Coropuna is ongoing.{{sfn|Weibel|Frangipane-Gysel|Hunziker|1978|p=246}} \n\nCoropuna is part of the [[volcanic arc]] of southern Peru{{sfn|Garc\u00eda Z\u00fa\u00f1iga|Mari\u00f1o Salazar|Valdivia Humerez|2018|p=117}} and is considered to be a member of the Barroso volcanic arc.{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=9}} There are over six hundred volcanoes in southern Peru{{sfn|Venturelli|Fragipane|Weibel|Antiga|1978|p=213}} and the entire Cordillera Occidental from southern Peru to northern Chile is covered with volcanic rocks, although present-day volcanic activity is scarce.{{sfn|Weibel|Frangipane-Gysel|Hunziker|1978|p=245}} Many of the older volcanoes are deeply eroded by glaciation while younger volcanoes often still resemble cones.{{sfn|Bullard|1962|p=443}}\n\nVolcanic activity in the Andes occurred during three eras. The first was between 195 and 190{{nbsp;}}million years ago in the Early [[Jurassic]], and generated the [[Geology of Peru#Mesozoic (251-66&nbsp;million years ago)|Chocolate Formation]]. The second between 78&nbsp;and 50{{nbsp;}}million years ago (Late [[Cretaceous]] to Early Eocene) generated the Toquepala Formation and the Andean [[batholith]]s.{{sfn|Thouret|Gunnell|Jicha|Paquette|2017|p=3}} Volcanic activity in southern Peru commenced about 13{{nbsp;}}million years ago in the Miocene.{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=57}} One volcanic unit{{Spaced en dash}}after being folded and eroded{{Spaced en dash}}was covered by a second lava and [[tuff]] unit which in turn was followed by the emplacement of large volcanoes.{{sfn|Bullard|1962|p=443}} Ignimbrites and stratovolcano activity, at times subdivided into a \"rhyolitic\" and an \"andesitic\" formation, alternated.{{sfn|Weibel|Frangipane-Gysel|Hunziker|1978|p=245}}\n\n=== Basement ===\nCoropuna is constructed atop of 14{{nbsp;}}million year old ignimbrites{{sfn|Venturelli|Fragipane|Weibel|Antiga|1978|p=214}} and lava flows of [[Neogene]] age.{{sfn|Forget|Thouret|Kuentz|Fontugne|2008|p=16}} Individual ignimbrites crop out mainly in valleys; on the highlands they are buried beneath more recent volcanic products.{{sfn|Weibel|Frangipane-Gysel|Hunziker|1978|p=246}} The volcanic basement includes the Miocene to [[Plio-Pleistocene]] [[Tacaza Formation|Tacaza]], [[Huaylillas Formation|Huaylillas]], [[Sencca Formation|Sencca]] and [[Barroso Formation, Peru|Barroso Formations]]; the latter formation includes Coropuna itself. Below these formations lie the sedimentary Murco and Socosani formations and the Yura Group, which are [[sediment]]s of Jurassic-Cretaceous age with intruded [[pluton]]s of the same age; finally there is a Basal Complex of [[Precambrian]] age.{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=37}}\n\n=== Faults and lineaments ===\nThe basement is cut by faults and [[lineament]]s such as the [[Pampacolca Fault]] on the southern side of the volcano and the [[Pumaranra lineament|Pumaranra]] and [[Cerro Casulla lineament]]s,{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=57}} which trend southeast{{en dash}}northwest and northeast{{en dash}}southwest, respectively. One east\u2013west lineament may have influenced the recent volcanism;{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=58}} the alignment of Coropuna with [[Sara Sara]], [[Solimana]] and [[El Misti]] may indicate a tectonic control on the volcano in general.{{sfn|Caldas Vidal|1993|p=35}} On the soutern flank, Holocene [[normal fault]]s have offset lava flows and streams.{{sfn|de Silva|Francis|1990|p=292}}\n\n=== Composition ===\nThe rocks released by Coropuna are dark brown to black and [[porphyritic]].{{sfn|Weibel|Frangipane-Gysel|Hunziker|1978|p=248}} They consist of [[andesite]],{{sfn|Campos|2015|p=2}} [[dacite]],{{sfn|Palenque|Ni\u00f1o de Guzm\u00e1n|Choque|\u00c1lvarez|2018|p=104}} [[rhyodacite]],{{sfn|Weibel|Frangipane-Gysel|Hunziker|1978|p=251}} [[rhyolite]],{{sfn|Venturelli|Fragipane|Weibel|Antiga|1978|p=215}} trachy-[[basaltic andesite]], [[trachyandesite]] and [[trachydacite]].{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=88}} The more recent lava flows have been dacitic{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=49}} or trachydacitic.{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=3}} [[Phenocryst]] phases include [[amphibole]], [[biotite]], [[plagioclase]], [[pyroxene]] and [[titanomagnetite]].{{sfn|Venturelli|Fragipane|Weibel|Antiga|1978|p=214}} Aside from the volcanic rocks, deposits of [[salt]]s, [[sulfur]] and [[travertine]] produced by [[hot spring]]s are found on the southern flank.{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=26}}\n\nThe volcanic rocks define a [[calc-alkaline]]{{sfn|Venturelli|Fragipane|Weibel|Antiga|1978|p=215}} [[potassium]]-rich suite which resembles that of{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=88}} Chilean{{sfn|Weibel|Frangipane-Gysel|Hunziker|1978|p=250}} and Peruvian volcanoes such as Tutupaca.{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=88}} They contain large amounts of [[rubidium]], [[strontium]] and [[barium]].{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=88}} Complicated processes{{sfn|Venturelli|Fragipane|Weibel|Antiga|1978|p=225}} of crystallisation and interaction with Earth's [[Crust (geology)|crust]] appear to have produced the magma.{{sfn|Venturelli|Fragipane|Weibel|Antiga|1978|p=226}}\n\n== Eruption history ==\nThe beginning of Coropuna's growth has variously been placed over 5{{nbsp;}}million years ago,{{sfn|Tosdal|Farrar|Clark|1981|p=168}} during the [[Pliocene]]{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=43}} or late Miocene, but most of its structure developed during the Quaternary.{{sfn|Bromley|Hall|Rademaker|Todd|2011|p=306}} Volcanic activity has been subdivided into two stages: [[explosive eruption]]s during the now mostly eroded Coropuna I stage produced volcanic ash, pyroclastic flows and [[pumice]] but also lava flows, while Coropuna II above {{convert|6000|m}} elevation erupted lava flows from the now snow-covered vents.{{sfn|Palenque|Ni\u00f1o de Guzm\u00e1n|Choque|\u00c1lvarez|2018|p=108}}{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=44}} The existence of a Coropuna III sequence has been proposed.{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=49}} The most recent eruption products have been described as the \"Andahua Group\".{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=87}} About 5.3{{nbsp;}}million years ago, the Sunjillpa volcano was active southwest from Coropuna,<ref name=\"Mapa2017\" /> while Pumaranra is of Pliocene to Quaternary age.{{sfn|Palenque|Ni\u00f1o de Guzm\u00e1n|Choque|\u00c1lvarez|2018|p=108}}\n\nA major ignimbrite eruption took place about 2{{nbsp;}}million years ago at Coropuna; its deposits have been identified west of the volcano{{sfn|Tosdal|Farrar|Clark|1981|p=169}}{{sfn|Palenque|Ni\u00f1o de Guzm\u00e1n|Choque|\u00c1lvarez|2018|p=104}} and it led to the destruction of the edifice, which later re-formed on the remains of the old volcano.{{sfn|Weibel|Frangipane-Gysel|Hunziker|1978|p=245}} The occurrence of explosive eruptions during a mostly effusive activity has been found at Chachani and Sara Sara as well.{{sfn|Weibel|Frangipane-Gysel|Hunziker|1978|p=245}}\n\nIn addition, the Upper Sencca Ignimbrite, the Lower Sencca Ignimbrite<ref name=\"\u00c7ubuk\u00e7u2012\" /> and the Chuquibamba (Huaylillas{{sfn|Cubukcu|Paquette|Jicha|Thouret|2016|p=11}}) Ignimbrite{{sfn|Cubukcu|Paquette|Jicha|Thouret|2016|p=17}} may have originated here as well;{{sfn|Cubukcu|Paquette|Jicha|Thouret|2016|p=21}} the latter was produced by a [[Volcanic Explosivity Index|volcanic explosivity index]] 7&nbsp;class \"super-eruption\"{{sfn|Cubukcu|Paquette|Jicha|Thouret|2016|p=19}} between 14.3 and 13.2{{nbsp;}}million years ago in the [[Middle Miocene]].{{sfn|Cubukcu|Paquette|Jicha|Thouret|2016|p=20}} The Upper Sencca Ignimbrites are a {{nowrap|2.09\u20131.76 million}} years old{{sfn|Cubukcu|Paquette|Jicha|Thouret|2016|p=17}} composite ignimbrite{{sfn|Cubukcu|Paquette|Jicha|Thouret|2016|p=15}} which form a {{convert|10|-|30|m|abbr=on}} thick apron around Coropuna and other regional volcanoes; Coropuna appears to have formed on top of one of the Upper Sencca Ignimbrite vents.{{sfn|Cubukcu|Paquette|Jicha|Thouret|2016|p=17}}\n\nAfter a hiatus,{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=55}} volcanic activity continued into the [[Pleistocene]].{{sfn|Palenque|Ni\u00f1o de Guzm\u00e1n|Choque|\u00c1lvarez|2018|p=104}} Several lava flows on the western and central sides of Coropuna have been dated, yielding ages ranging from {{nowrap|410,000 \u00b1 9,000}} to {{nowrap|62,600 \u00b1 4,300 years}} ago.<ref name=\"Mapa2017\" /> During the last glacial maximum, Coropuna was inactive{{sfn|Thouret|Juvigne|Mari\u00f1o|Moscol|2002|p=3}} and moraines buried its lava flows.{{sfn|Bromley|Thouret|Schimmelpfennig|Mari\u00f1o|2019|p=3}} However, one{{sfn|Thouret|Juvigne|Mari\u00f1o|Moscol|2002|p=3}} or two tephra layers on a moraine close to the village of Viraco on the southern side have been dated to be about 41,000 and 30,000{{Spaced en dash}}31,000{{nbsp;}}years old. These ages correspond to [[radiocarbon]] ages of {{nowrap|37,370 \u00b1 1,160}} and {{nowrap|27,200 \u00b1 300 years}}. These tephras may have originated in [[fissure eruption]]s associated with the three recent lava flows.{{sfn|Forget|Thouret|Kuentz|Fontugne|2008|p=22}} In postglacial times [[lava bomb]]s, [[lapilli]] and volcanic ash were deposited on previously glaciated terrain.{{sfn|Palenque|Ni\u00f1o de Guzm\u00e1n|Choque|\u00c1lvarez|2018|p=108}} Pumice deposits may have formed during the Holocene.{{sfn|Vela|C\u00e1ceres|Calder\u00f3n|Chijcheapaza|2016|p=9}}\n\n=== Holocene ===\nNo eruptions of Coropuna during historical<ref name=\"DeggChester2005\" /> or modern times are known,{{sfn|Marinque|Marino|Enderlin|Edwards|2018|p=175}} and the volcano was considered to be long-extinct.{{sfn|Bullard|1962|p=444}} However, young-looking{{sfn|de Silva|Francis|1990|p=292}} [[Lava#\u02bbA\u02bb\u0101|\u02bba\u02bb\u0101 lava]]{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=15}} or [[Lava#Block lava flows|block lava]]{{sfn|Bromley|Thouret|Schimmelpfennig|Mari\u00f1o|2019|p=3}} flows erupted during the Holocene and in part overlie late-glacial moraines.{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=49}}{{sfn|Bromley|Hall|Rademaker|Todd|2011|p=306}}{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=15}} Their vents are now hidden beneath glacier ice{{sfn|Cuber|Panajew|Ga\u0142a\u015b|2015|p=63}} and the flows have been affected by later glacial advances.{{sfn|Bromley|Thouret|Schimmelpfennig|Mari\u00f1o|2019|p=8-9}} These lava flows are found on the west{{en dash}}northwest, south{{en dash}}southeast and northeast side of the mountain:{{sfn|Bromley|Hall|Rademaker|Todd|2011|p=307}}\n\n* A northwesterly lava flow \u2013 Coropuna's longest{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=49}} at {{convert|8.5|km|abbr=on}} \u2013 occupies the Cerro Sepulturayoc valley.{{sfn|\u00dabeda|Palacios|V\u00e1zquez-Selem|2012|p=3}} It has been dated to about 6,000{{nbsp;}}years ago,{{sfn|\u00dabeda|Palacios|V\u00e1zquez-Selem|2012|p=3}} but research published in 2019 has suggested it may have erupted somewhat earlier, during the [[Late Glacial]] period.{{sfn|Bromley|Thouret|Schimmelpfennig|Mari\u00f1o|2019|p=12}}\n* A southeasterly flow lies in the Cospanja valley and is either {{nowrap|1,100 \u00b1 100}}{{sfn|\u00dabeda|Palacios|V\u00e1zquez-Selem|2012|p=4}} or {{nowrap|700 \u00b1 200 years}} old,<ref name=\"Mapa2017\" /> the latter age being derived from [[Cosmogenic dating|cosmogenic isotope dating]].{{sfn|Garc\u00eda Z\u00fa\u00f1iga|Mari\u00f1o Salazar|Valdivia Humerez|2018|p=117}} It was probably formed during a single eruption and is {{convert|4|km|spell=in|}} long.{{sfn|Bromley|Thouret|Schimmelpfennig|Mari\u00f1o|2019|p=6}}\n* A dark, young-looking lava<ref name=\"GVPP\" /> flow runs northeasterly{{sfn|Palenque|Ni\u00f1o de Guzm\u00e1n|Choque|\u00c1lvarez|2018|p=105}} in the Que\u00f1ua Ranra valley{{sfn|Palenque|Ni\u00f1o de Guzm\u00e1n|Choque|\u00c1lvarez|2018|p=108}} and is {{convert|5|km|spell=in}} long.{{sfn|Bromley|Thouret|Schimmelpfennig|Mari\u00f1o|2019|p=8}} The eruption took place about {{nowrap|2,100 \u00b1 200 years}} ago{{sfn|Palenque|Ni\u00f1o de Guzm\u00e1n|Choque|\u00c1lvarez|2018|p=109}} according to cosmogenic isotope dating.{{sfn|Garc\u00eda Z\u00fa\u00f1iga|Mari\u00f1o Salazar|Valdivia Humerez|2018|p=117}} Its deposition was preceded by the eruption of lava bombs that cover the valley and by the production of a lahar that advanced {{convert|14|km|abbr=on}} from its source. Whether a secondary lava flow in the same valley occurred at the same time or later is not clear, as that flow has not yet been dated.{{sfn|Palenque|Ni\u00f1o de Guzm\u00e1n|Choque|\u00c1lvarez|2018|p=109}}\n\nThe ages of the flows indicate an eastward shift in activity.<ref name=\"\u00dabedaPalacio2012\" /> The southeasterly and northeasterly flows may have been erupted within 500&nbsp;years from the same fissure,{{sfn|Bromley|Thouret|Schimmelpfennig|Mari\u00f1o|2019|p=12}} while the eruption of the northwesterly flow might be a consequence of the retreat of the ice cap.{{sfn|Bromley|Thouret|Schimmelpfennig|Mari\u00f1o|2019|pp=2, 13}} These lava flows are the most recent manifestation of volcanic activity{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=3}} and they imply that Coropuna is still active;{{sfn|Marinque|Marino|Enderlin|Edwards|2018|p=175}} it is thus considered to be a [[dormant volcano]], rather than an extinct one.{{sfn|Thouret|Juvigne|Mari\u00f1o|Moscol|2002|p=2}} There is no evidence of Holocene tephras in [[peat bog]] [[drill core]]s{{sfn|Thouret|Juvigne|Mari\u00f1o|Moscol|2002|p=3}} and volcanism at Coropuna since the last ice age has been primarily [[effusive eruption|effusive]].{{sfn|Bromley|Thouret|Schimmelpfennig|Mari\u00f1o|2019|p=12}}\n\n=== Present day status ===\n[[File:Steam vents on Coropuna Este (30293366136).jpg|thumb|Steam rising on Coropuna Este]]\nThe volcano is still hydrothermally active.{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=3}} Six hot springs are found on Coropuna, mostly on the southeastern foot,{{sfn|INGEMMET|2015|p=12}} such as at Acopallpa, Antaura, Viques, Ccollpa, and Aguas Calientes and, on its northern flank, at Huaman\u00ed Loma. Their water temperatures range between {{convert|18|and|51|C}}.{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=25}} With the exception of the last two, which are situated in glacial terrain, these hot springs rise within valleys via rock fractures.{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=26}} Geochemical analyses of the water from these springs published in 2015 show no major variations in composition, implying a stable volcanic system.{{sfn|INGEMMET|2015|p=18}} Whether [[solfataric]] or [[fumarolic]] activity occurs at Coropuna is unclear,<ref name=\"GVP\" />{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=25}} and the thick glaciation indicates that the summit craters have no thermal activity.{{sfn|de Silva|Francis|1990|p=292}}\n\nSome of the hot springs on Coropuna are used for bathing.{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=26}} The volcano had been considered a potential site for [[geothermal power]] production,<ref name=\"DiazHuaina1988\" /> but research published in 1998 concluded that the available energy of the Coropuna area was insufficient.{{sfn|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|Steinm\u00fcller|1998|p=42}}\n\nThe first volcano activity report published in 2018 noted ongoing [[seismic]] activity involving [[Volcano tectonic earthquake|volcano-tectonic earthquakes]].<ref name=\"IGdP2018\" /> [[Seismic swarm]]s were observed at Coropuna after the [[2001 southern Peru earthquake]]{{sfn|Lohman|Pritchard|Holtkamp|2011|p=139}} and were possibly triggered by that earthquake.{{sfn|Lohman|Pritchard|Holtkamp|2011|p=144}} Observations of deformation of the volcanic edifice have shown that [[gravitational instability]] and [[soil]] water absorption result in movements of part of the volcano but, as a whole, Coropuna shows no evidence of volcanic deformation.{{sfn|INGEMMET|2015|pp=27\u201328}}\n\n=== Hazards and monitoring ===\nThe Peruvian [[INGEMMET|Instituto Geol\u00f3gico Minero y Metal\u00fargico]] (INGEMMET) monitors Coropuna for activity. It uses data such as the composition of hot spring waters{{sfn|INGEMMET|2015|p=11}} and the shape of the volcano as estimated by [[Satellite imagery|satellite images]],{{sfn|INGEMMET|2015|p=25}} [[GPS]] and [[geodesy]],{{sfn|INGEMMET|2015|p=27}} as well as information from five seismic stations.<ref name=\"MdA2019\" /> A volcanic hazard map has been published{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=75}} and there are regular status reports published by the Peruvian government.<ref name=\"MdA2019b\" /> About 90,000 people live in risk areas,<ref name=\"MdA2019\" /> and the sites most in danger are towns in the steep southern valleys.{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=88}}\n\nTogether with [[El Misti]], Sabancaya and Ubinas, Coropuna is considered to be one of Peru's most dangerous volcanoes.{{sfn|Vela|C\u00e1ceres|Calder\u00f3n|Chijcheapaza|2016|p=28}} The presence of an ice cap, and therefore the risk of [[incandescent]] volcanic rocks melting that ice, creates a hazard of lahars, or mudflows, such as those that in 1985 killed over 23,000 people at [[Nevado del Ruiz]] volcano in [[Colombia]].{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=61}}{{sfn|Marinque|Marino|Enderlin|Edwards|2018|p=175}} The risk to life is further increased by Coropuna's steep slopes and by the concentration of people in nearby valleys.{{sfn|\u00dabeda|Palacios|V\u00e1zquez-Selem|2012|p=1}} The terrain around the volcano has one of the greatest topographic reliefs in the world and a number of towns lie on the floor of the Majes valley, right down to the Pacific Ocean where the district capital [[Caman\u00e1]]{{sfn|de Silva|Francis|1990|p=292}} with 20,000 inhabitants is situated.<ref name=\"DeggChester2005\" /> Although there is no evidence of past mudflows of such size, lahars could reach as far as the coast,{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=69}} affecting a number of towns{{sfn|Vela|C\u00e1ceres|Calder\u00f3n|Chijcheapaza|2016|loc=Anexo No.4}} and infrastructure such as roads, [[antenna (radio)|antenna]]s and small [[hydropower]] plants.{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=61}} According to the 2007 census, 110,481 people lived in the provinces that span Coropuna and lie downstream of it.{{sfn|Marinque|Marino|Enderlin|Edwards|2018|p=175}}\n\nLava flows are also a potential danger at Coropuna.{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=88}} Other hazards with lesser probabilities are [[Lateral eruption|directed volcanic blast]]s, lava dome collapses,{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=88}} fast-moving massive pyroclastic flows{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=73}} and flows of pumice and volcanic ash,{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=88}} lava bombs{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=70}} and [[shock wave]]s from volcanic explosions.{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=76}}\n\n== Climate ==\n\n=== Precipitation ===\nCoropuna lies between the semi-humid Altiplano and the [[arid]] western slope of the Andes.{{sfn|Kuentz|Thouret|Ledru|Forget|2011|p=236}} Its climate is [[semi-arid]], with precipitation at {{convert|6080|m|abbr=on}} elevation reaching {{convert|390|mm/year|in/year}}.{{sfn|Bromley|Hall|Rademaker|Todd|2011|p=306}} Other reported precipitation values range between {{convert|700|mm/year|in/year|abbr=on}}{{sfn|Weide|Fritz|Brinson|Thompson|2017|p=2}} and {{convert|1000|mm/year|in/year|abbr=on}}.{{sfn|Bromley|Schaefer|Winckler|Hall|2009|p=2515}} Lower down the mountain, at altitudes between at {{convert|3000|and|4000|m|abbr=on}}, annual precipitation levels increase to between {{convert|226|and|560|mm/year|in/year|abbr=on}} (semi-humid). Even further down, at altitudes around {{convert|2000|-|3000|m|abbr=on}}, they decrease again to {{convert|98|-|227|mm/year|in/year|abbr=on}} (desert).{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=7}} Cold water brought from [[Antarctica]] along the Pacific Ocean by the [[Humboldt Current]],{{sfn|Palenque|Ni\u00f1o de Guzm\u00e1n|Choque|\u00c1lvarez|2018|p=99}} the presence of a stable [[anticyclone]] {{sfn|\u00dabeda Palenque|2013|p=25}} and of a [[temperature inversion]] over the Pacific, and the Andean [[rainshadow]] are all responsible for this dryness.{{sfn|Bromley|Hall|Rademaker|Todd|2011|p=306}} \n\nMost precipitation falls as [[hail]] or snow.{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=7}} This happens mostly during the summer{{sfn|Bromley|Hall|Rademaker|Todd|2011|p=306}} [[wet season]], between December and March,{{sfn|Bromley|Schaefer|Winckler|Hall|2009|p=2515}} when the [[ITCZ]] moves south{{sfn|Palenque|Ni\u00f1o de Guzm\u00e1n|Choque|\u00c1lvarez|2018|p=98}} and a summer [[monsoon]] is active over South America.{{sfn|Palenque|Ni\u00f1o de Guzm\u00e1n|Choque|\u00c1lvarez|2018|p=99}} Most precipitation is brought by easterly winds coming from the [[Amazon basin|Amazon]] and the [[Atlantic Ocean]], whereas the westerly winds that dominate during the dry season do not carry much moisture.{{sfn|Campos|2015|p=2}} Thus, humidity generally decreases in a westward direction.{{sfn|\u00dabeda Palenque|2013|p=25}}\n\nThe amount of precipitation is modulated by the [[El Ni\u00f1o Southern Oscillation]]. During phases of El Ni\u00f1o the weather is drier, snow cover smaller and glacier retreat increases.{{sfn|Forget|Thouret|Kuentz|Fontugne|2008|p=31}}<ref name=\"Kochtitzky2016\" /> Over longer timespans, precipitation in the region increases whenever [[iceberg]] discharge and cooling occur in the [[North Atlantic]]. This was the case during the [[Heinrich event]]s and the Younger Dryas when lakes formed on the Bolivian [[Altiplano]]: The [[Sajsi]] formed about 25,000\u201319,000{{nbsp;}}years ago, [[Lake Tauca|Tauca]] about 18,000\u201314,000 and Coipasa 13,000\u201311,000{{nbsp;}}years ago.{{sfn|Palenque|Ni\u00f1o de Guzm\u00e1n|Choque|\u00c1lvarez|2018|p=99}} Cold periods in the [[Southern Hemisphere]] such as the Antarctic Cold Reversal between 14,500 and 12,900{{nbsp;}}years ago may have pushed the [[polar front]] north and increased precipitation as well.{{sfn|\u00dabeda Palenque|2013|p=25}} That increased precipitation may have delayed the retreat of Coropuna's glaciers after the end of the last glacial maximum.{{sfn|\u00dabeda Palenque|2013|p=27}} Coropuna experienced moist conditions during the early Holocene, whereas the late Holocene beginning 5,200{{nbsp;}}years ago was drier there,{{sfn|Kuentz|Ledru|Thouret|2011|p=1224}} with a pronounced dry period lasting from 5,200 to 3,000{{nbsp;}}years ago.<ref name=\"Escobar-Torrez2018\" />\n\n=== Temperature ===\nTemperatures decrease with altitude gain, and at lower elevations around {{convert|2000|-|3000|m|abbr=on}} they average {{convert|12|-|17|C|abbr=on}}. Between {{convert|3000|and|4000|m|abbr=on}} they average  {{convert|7.8|C|abbr=on}} and at {{convert|4000|-|5200|m|abbr=on}} elevation they average {{convert|0|-|6|C|abbr=on}}. At altitudes above {{convert|5200|m|abbr=on}} they remain below freezing.{{sfn|Valenzuela Ortiz|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Ju\u00e1rez|2001|p=7}} Temperatures fluctuate more over daily timescales than over seasonal ones when measured close to the glaciers.{{sfn|Silverio|Jaquet|2012|p=5878}} Southerly cold waves can sometimes reach Coropuna, leaving traces in ice cores in the form of southern [[pollen]].{{sfn|Schotterer|Delachaux|Ledru|Angelis|2009|pp=32\u201333}} During the Little Ice Age, at {{convert|5000|-|5200|m|abbr=on}} elevation temperatures decreased to {{convert|-5|to|-7|C|abbr=on}}.{{sfn|Forget|Thouret|Kuentz|Fontugne|2008|p=30}} Warm fluctuations between about 2,200 and 900{{nbsp;}}years ago, plus a cold fluctuation between around 970 to 1010 [[AD]], are also recorded.{{sfn|Engel|Skrzypek|Chuman|\u0160efrna|2014|p=73}}\n\n== Vegetation, fauna and agriculture ==\n[[File:Yareta Peru.jpg|thumb|Yareta on Coropuna|alt=Cushion-shaped plants grow in a wide rock-strewn valley]]\nMost of the region is covered by [[puna grassland]], with the exception of isolated ''[[Polylepis]]'' woods to the southwest of the volcano, plus other different vegetation types to the west and southeast.{{sfn|Kuentz|Mera|Ledru|Thouret|2007|p=1765}} Peat bogs are present on the southern and southwestern sides of Coropuna, and some of these have been drilled to obtain [[sediment core]]s.{{sfn|Forget|Thouret|Kuentz|Fontugne|2008|p=18}}{{sfn|Forget|Thouret|Kuentz|Fontugne|2008|p=17}} Elsewhere, agriculture is widespread around Coropuna.{{sfn|Forget|Thouret|Kuentz|Fontugne|2008|p=18}} Insects such as beetles and [[hymenoptera]]ns, birds such as the [[Andean condor]],{{sfn|Cuber|Panajew|Ga\u0142a\u015b|2015|p=67}} fish and mammals such as the [[alpaca]], [[llama]]{{sfn|Kuentz|Thouret|Ledru|Forget|2011|p=242}} and [[vicu\u00f1a]] occur in the region.{{sfn|Cuber|Panajew|Ga\u0142a\u015b|2015|p=67}} Several new species of [[butterfly]] have been discovered there.<ref name=\"Larico2018\" />\n\nThe mountain has several distinct vegetation belts:\n* Between {{convert|800|and|2500|m|abbr=on}} lies [[steppe]] vegetation with ''[[Ambrosia]]'' [[shrub]]s and [[cacti]]. [[Irrigation]] permits the cultivation of garlic, olive, onion, potato, rice, sugar cane and wheat. [[Pasture]]s are also present.{{sfn|Kuentz|Thouret|Ledru|Forget|2011|pp=241\u2013242}}\n* The steppe vegetation is also present between {{convert|2500|and|3500|m|abbr=on}} in the \"pre-Puna\", but it is denser here{{sfn|Kuentz|Thouret|Ledru|Forget|2011|p=242}} and includes shrubs of the family [[Asteraceae]], such as ''Ambrosia'', ''[[Diplostephium]]'' and ''[[Senecio]]''.{{sfn|Kuentz|Ledru|Thouret|2011|p=1216}} Crops grown here include [[alfalfa]], but there is also some [[dairy farming]] and  the planting of [[eucalyptus]] and [[pine tree]]s  as a wood supply for the local population.{{sfn|Kuentz|Thouret|Ledru|Forget|2011|p=242}}\n* Between {{convert|3000|and|4000|m|abbr=on}} lies a so-called \"supra-tropical facies\" on soils overlying lava flows. It includes shrubs and [[Thorns, spines, and prickles|thorny]] vegetation in very wet and very dry areas, respectively. Agriculture is practised here, including the growing of [[kiwicha]], maize, [[quinoa]] and vegetables on [[anthropogenic soils]]{{sfn|Kuentz|Mera|Ledru|Thouret|2007|pp=1767\u20131768}} and [[terrace (agriculture)|terrace]]d fields.{{sfn|Kuentz|Thouret|Ledru|Forget|2011|p=242}} Dominant natural plants between {{convert|3500|and|4000|m|abbr=on}} include herbaceous plants of the families [[Fabaceae]] and [[Solanaceae]], as well as shrubs of the Asteraceae.{{sfn|Kuentz|Ledru|Thouret|2011|p=1216}}\n* Between {{convert|4000|and|4800|m|abbr=on}} vegetation is found in [[marsh]]es and peat bogs where sufficient water is available, in the form of relic ''Polylepis'' woodlands as well as herbaceous puna vegetation{{sfn|Kuentz|Mera|Ledru|Thouret|2007|pp=1768\u20131769}} which is particularly prolific during the wet season. These areas are used for pasture of [[alpaca]]s and [[llama]]s, and for [[fishing]] in wetlands and ''Polylepis'' woods; hamlets are found close to wetlands and forests.{{sfn|Kuentz|Thouret|Ledru|Forget|2011|p=242}} Plant genera found here include ''[[Baccharis]]'', ''[[Calamagrostis]]'', ''[[Chuquiraga]]'', ''[[Festuca]]'', ''[[Parastrephia]]'', ''Senecio'' and ''[[Stipa]]''.{{sfn|Kuentz|Ledru|Thouret|2011|p=1216}}\n* Above {{convert|4800|m|abbr=on}} lies the so-called \"Puna brava\", with herbs and deep-rooted plants that have all adapted to withstand permafrost conditions.{{sfn|Kuentz|Mera|Ledru|Thouret|2007|p=1769}} The [[cushion plant]], [[yareta]], which is used as a fuel source, is the dominant plant in this belt.{{sfn|Kuentz|Thouret|Ledru|Forget|2011|p=243}} Other plants from the [[Apiaceae]] and Asteraceae also occur.{{sfn|Weide|Fritz|Brinson|Thompson|2017|p=3}} Vegetation, including [[Jarava ichu|ichu grass]] and yareta, exist up to about {{convert|5|km|abbr=on|spell=in}} elevation; higher elevations are unvegetated.{{sfn|Bromley|Hall|Rademaker|Todd|2011|p=307}}\n\n== Archaeology and religious importance ==\nNumerous archaeological sites lie on Coropuna, especially at the southern and northern bases of the volcano and on its western slope.{{sfn|Forget|Thouret|Kuentz|Fontugne|2008|p=18}} Among these are funerary towers known as ''[[chullpa]]s''.<ref name=\"Duchesne2005\" /> Some of these western sites are on the ice cap.{{sfn|Forget|Thouret|Kuentz|Fontugne|2008|p=18}} Proposals have been made to make the area of Coropuna including these archaeological sites into a [[protected area]].<ref name=\"Goicochea2009\" />\n\nThe coastal regions of Peru were first occupied 11,000 and 9,000{{nbsp;}}years [[Before Christ|BC]].{{sfn|Kuentz|Thouret|Ledru|Forget|2011|p=243}} Evidence of the presence of [[hunter-gatherer]]s near Coropuna first appear in the archaeological record in the caves of Cavalca and Pintasayoc, respectively north and south of the volcano. In the latter cave, [[rock painting]]s interpreted as being 7,000{{Spaced en dash}}3,000{{nbsp;}}years BC have been found.{{sfn|Kuentz|Thouret|Ledru|Forget|2011|p=246}} The first human activity at Coropuna in the Cuncaicha [[cave]] north of the volcano began shortly after the final retreat of glaciers from the mountain.{{sfn|Sandweiss|\u00c1lvarez|Reid|Leach|2014|p=469}} The region around the volcano was settled over the last 4,000{{nbsp;}}years.{{sfn|Kuentz|Thouret|Ledru|Forget|2011|p=236}}\n\n=== Inca times ===\nA larger number of archaeological sites go back to the 2nd Intermediate Period{{sfn|Kuentz|Thouret|Ledru|Forget|2011|pp=246\u2013248}} and during the Inca era. The Inca expanded preexisting irrigation and terrace systems which are in part still existing today.{{sfn|Kuentz|Thouret|Ledru|Forget|2011|p=248}} These include the highest irrigation system in the world<ref name=\"Ch\u00e1vez2001\" /> which was possibly constructed on Coropuna to allow the cultivation of bitter potatoes.<ref name=\"Orellana2017\" /> Inca sites are often found at higher elevations than the sites left by preceding civilisations; the highest one is located at {{convert|5700|m|abbr=on}} elevation{{sfn|Kuentz|Thouret|Ledru|Forget|2011|p=249}} and there is evidence of Inca presence to {{convert|6200|m|abbr=on}} elevation.<ref name=\"Ch\u00e1vez2001\" /> In addition, an important branch of the [[Inca road system]] passes by the western foot of Coropuna.<ref name=\"Ch\u00e1vez2001\" /> The region was densely populated; the close location of the mountains and favourable climatic conditions facilitated its settlement.{{sfn|Baca|Molak|Sobczyk|W\u0119gle\u0144ski|2014|p=3}}\n\nAs noted by [[Spaniards|Spanish]] chroniclers<ref name=\"Woloszyn2010\" /> such as [[Pedro de Cieza de Le\u00f3n]],{{sfn|Urton|Hagen|2015|p=105}} Coropuna played an important role in Inca religion and an important temple was situated there,{{sfn|Zi\u00f3\u0142kowski|2008|p=131}} possibly at [[Mawk'allaqta, Castilla|Maucallacta]].{{sfn|Zi\u00f3\u0142kowski|2008|p=145}} Pedro de Cieza de Le\u00f3n considered Coropuna to be the fifth most important holy site of the Inca empire.{{sfn|Urton|Hagen|2015|p=105}} One archaeological site on the volcano may have been a stopover for religious ceremonies to its summit.{{sfn|Zi\u00f3\u0142kowski|2008|p=138}} ''[[Capacocha]]'', a form of [[human sacrifice]], were offered to the mountain;<ref name=\"Woloszyn2010\" /> reportedly, in 1965, a [[mummy]] was found there.<ref name=\"Schobinger1999\" />\n\n==== Maucallacta and Acchaymarca ====\nAmong the archaeological sites at Coropuna is the important Inca site of Maucallacta, on the southwestern flank of the mountain.{{sfn|Sobczyk|2012|p=215}} Some of the structures there were built to evoke the appearance of the mountain.{{sfn|Sobczyk|2012|p=219}} A royal residence, an [[oracle]] and a political unit were associated with Maucallacta,{{sfn|Zi\u00f3\u0142kowski|2008|pp=131\u2013132}} and the oracle of Coropuna would have answered the rulers' queries all year round.{{sfn|Urton|Hagen|2015|p=211}} The Maucallacta site was probably the most important one at Coropuna; the western summit today known as \"La Ni\u00f1a\" was apparently also significant.{{sfn|Zi\u00f3\u0142kowski|2008|p=154}}\n\nAnother important site associated with Coropuna is Acchaymarca, to the west of the mountain,{{sfn|Baca|Molak|Sobczyk|W\u0119gle\u0144ski|2014|p=2}} where about 280 Inca stone structures have been found.{{sfn|Baca|Molak|Sobczyk|W\u0119gle\u0144ski|2014|p=3}} It is likely that many pilgrims came there for ceremonies honouring the ''[[Apu (god)|apus]]'' of Coropuna and Solimana.{{sfn|Baca|Molak|Sobczyk|W\u0119gle\u0144ski|2014|p=8}}\n\n== Mythology, religion and legends ==\nIn the Inca Empire, Coropuna was a [[Sacred mountains|sacred mountain]],{{sfn|Sobczyk|2012|p=215}} especially for the people of [[Cotahuasi]].<ref name=\"MINCETUR2019\" /> It was regarded as the most important mountain deity (''[[apu (god)|apu]]'') of the southern region,<ref name=\"Ch\u00e1vez2001\" /> and the second-most important in the [[cosmology]] of the Andes.<ref name=\"Trawick2003\" /> The mountain was considered to be an abode of the dead{{sfn|Fourtan\u00e9|2001|p=16}} \u2013 a large village where holy people received the souls of the departed, who lived there in the afterlife.<ref name=\"Trawick2003\" />{{sfn|Fourtan\u00e9|2001|p=17}} In different mythologies Coropuna is instead the starting point for the deceased on a journey to [[Surimana]].{{sfn|Fourtan\u00e9|2001|p=17}} Sometimes Coropuna is seen as a male entity while Solimana volcano is seen as a female one.<ref name=\"Golte2004\" /> Local people continue to observe these ancient mortuary rites today.<ref name=\"Trawick2003\" /> \n\nAn enduring Franciscan influence from a colonial-era [[Cusco]] friary, the \"pious among today's Peruvian peasantry\" revere a \"Flying\" [[St Francis of Assisi]], who is believed to await the souls of the dead on top of Coropuna.<ref name=\"Lara2013\" /> Other poorly recorded legends are associated with Coropuna.{{sfn|Zi\u00f3\u0142kowski|2008|p=143}} One story narrates how a brother tried to deceive Coropuna and other mountains, and was turned into a deer.<ref name=\"Campos2018\" /> Another legend tells of a conflict between Coropuna and other local mountains against an interloping Inca.<ref name=\"Menaker2019\" /> A third story states that a troupe was transporting precious metals for Coropuna and Solimana when the animal leading it was shot by a hunter; the mountains then castrated the hunter.<ref name=\"Gose1986\" />\n\n== Climbing ==\nThe archaeological findings made on Coropuna indicate that the Inca may have reached the summit.<ref name=\"Echevarria1980\" /> [[Annie Peck]] and [[Hiram Bingham III]] each reached a summit of Coropuna in 1911; Annie Peck raised a banner saying \"Votes for Women\" on the summit she had ascended, which was slightly lower than the one reached by Bingham.<ref name=\"Smith2004\" /> This banner action was part of the [[women's suffrage]] campaigns that were taking place at that time, and meant to illustrate that women were just as capable as men of physical deeds.<ref name=\"Schultz2010\" /> Since then, other summits of the mountain have been ascended as well.<ref name=\"Hernandez2013\" />\n\nThe rugged area offers [[mountaineering]] opportunities.<ref name=\"MINCETUR2019\" /> Coropuna is normally ascended from Laguna Pallarcocha, from where a route along the western rib and glacier slopes leads up to a foresummit and then to the main summit. Along this way, a high camp can be set up at {{convert|5600|-|5800|m}} elevation. An ascent of Coropuna would normally be a three-day trip, and on the [[Grade (climbing)#International French adjectival system (IFAS)|French adjectival climbing scale]] the route is graded as Facile (F). Pallarcocha itself can be reached from a road that begins in the town of Chuquibamba.<ref name=\"Biggar2015\" />\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"Lara2013\">{{cite journal|last1=Lara|first1=Jaime|title=Francis Alive and Aloft: Franciscan Apocalypticism in the Colonial Andes|journal=The Americas|date=2013|volume=70|issue=2|pages=162\u2013163|doi=10.1353/tam.2013.0096|language=en|issn=0003-1615}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"AAC1990\">{{cite book |author1=American Alpine Club |title=The American alpine journal |date=1990 |publi